So one thing you
can do is work real

01:01:39.130 --> 01:01:41.140
hard to get rid of the tension.

01:01:41.140 --> 01:01:42.986
And that will just increase it.

01:01:42.986 --> 01:01:45.000
Right?

01:01:45.000 --> 01:01:49.612
So our job actually is
not to solve the tension.

01:01:53.180 --> 01:01:56.880
Just imagine that maybe
it's not actually a problem,

01:01:56.880 --> 01:02:01.860
that if you can cultivate
some wholesome qualities.

01:02:01.860 --> 01:02:05.470
So awareness is a very, very
wholesome, very powerful thing.

01:02:05.470 --> 01:02:07.490
So if you can just
be a little more

01:02:07.490 --> 01:02:10.840
aware that things
are really tense,

01:02:10.840 --> 01:02:13.040
that will tend to drain it out.

01:02:13.040 --> 01:02:19.020
The difficulty is that
there's this in-between stage.

01:02:19.020 --> 01:02:21.220
Some people call it the
dark night of the soul.

01:02:21.220 --> 01:02:23.980
I call them Alfred
Hitchcock moments.

01:02:23.980 --> 01:02:27.500
Where there is enough
awareness that when you're

01:02:27.500 --> 01:02:30.030
caught up and angry
at somebody, and when

01:02:30.030 --> 01:02:32.700
you want to throttle them,
you have enough clarity,

01:02:32.700 --> 01:02:35.560
have enough awareness
inside, that says wow.

01:02:35.560 --> 01:02:38.810
You know, I just
really-- I lost it here.

01:02:38.810 --> 01:02:40.720
But the awareness is
not quite strong enough

01:02:40.720 --> 01:02:43.280
to know what to do about it.

01:02:43.280 --> 01:02:46.320
So that's the point when
you try to clamp down on it.

01:02:46.320 --> 01:02:52.730
But actually frankly to
grab for peacefulness

01:02:52.730 --> 01:02:55.767
is just a form of
greed or aversion.

01:02:55.767 --> 01:02:56.600
Maybe it's aversion.

01:02:56.600 --> 01:02:58.090
We get rid of something.

01:02:58.090 --> 01:02:59.850
And so that doesn't help.

01:02:59.850 --> 01:03:03.400
But what you want
to do is to create--

01:03:03.400 --> 01:03:05.470
is to bring in more of
those wholesome qualities.

01:03:05.470 --> 01:03:11.450
And I would say those six
Rs is a really effective way

01:03:11.450 --> 01:03:15.480
to do that, because
it's kind of mechanical,

01:03:15.480 --> 01:03:18.540
so that you just start bringing
a little more awareness.

01:03:18.540 --> 01:03:20.790
Just knowing that particularly
if it's a deep pattern,

01:03:20.790 --> 01:03:23.210
it's not going to
disappear overnight.

01:03:23.210 --> 01:03:26.230
But you can get a
toe in the door.

01:03:26.230 --> 01:03:30.244
And then after you've been
able to do it a few times,

01:03:30.244 --> 01:03:31.910
then you get a little
bit of confidence.

01:03:31.910 --> 01:03:34.710
Then maybe, maybe,
maybe this will work.

01:03:34.710 --> 01:03:36.180
Maybe this will work.

01:03:49.950 --> 01:03:52.230
So as your walking out of
here, and you think, oh.

01:03:52.230 --> 01:03:56.272
I wish I'd asked that.

01:03:56.272 --> 01:03:57.105
This is your chance.

01:04:04.770 --> 01:04:06.690
AUDIENCE: Is everything
OK at some level?

01:04:09.640 --> 01:04:14.040
DOUG KRAFT: On some level, I
mean, that's a great question.

01:04:14.040 --> 01:04:15.913
It's actually a
pretty profound one.

01:04:21.440 --> 01:04:24.020
OK.

01:04:24.020 --> 01:04:25.200
Let me throw a curve at you.

01:04:25.200 --> 01:04:28.060
But that's a great question.

01:04:28.060 --> 01:04:31.520
So imagine this.

01:04:31.520 --> 01:04:35.720
Every day in your life you walk
into a room, take your clothes

01:04:35.720 --> 01:04:39.780
off, they take a picture of
you in a certain posture.

01:04:39.780 --> 01:04:42.276
You live 100 years.

01:04:42.276 --> 01:04:44.400
Now you take all those
frames and put them together

01:04:44.400 --> 01:04:47.750
into a movie that runs
from, say, 15 minutes.

01:04:47.750 --> 01:04:48.590
OK.

01:04:48.590 --> 01:04:50.210
And then just to
make it more fun,

01:04:50.210 --> 01:04:53.390
we start the movie a year before
you were born, and run it say,

01:04:53.390 --> 01:04:55.500
five years after your death.

01:04:55.500 --> 01:04:57.020
So I'm watching this film.

01:04:57.020 --> 01:05:01.130
And so at first
there is nothing.

01:05:01.130 --> 01:05:02.710
And then there is your mother.

01:05:02.710 --> 01:05:03.880
She starts to swell up.

01:05:03.880 --> 01:05:04.900
Pop out you come.

01:05:04.900 --> 01:05:08.000
When you're nursing and peeing
and pooping, and not doing

01:05:08.000 --> 01:05:08.500
too much.

01:05:08.500 --> 01:05:10.334
You go through all that stuff.

01:05:10.334 --> 01:05:11.750
But your body, you
know, it starts

01:05:11.750 --> 01:05:13.270
to stretch out a little bit.

01:05:13.270 --> 01:05:14.390
Maybe a little baby fat.

01:05:14.390 --> 01:05:15.090
It goes down a little bit.

01:05:15.090 --> 01:05:16.450
And there you are standing up.

01:05:16.450 --> 01:05:19.010
And maybe five
minutes into the film

01:05:19.010 --> 01:05:22.720
you know, you're coming
into adolescence.

01:05:22.720 --> 01:05:24.570
And there's that
sort of vitality

01:05:24.570 --> 01:05:26.750
of youth and young adults.

01:05:26.750 --> 01:05:29.740
And the body gets stronger.

01:05:29.740 --> 01:05:33.750
And then there's
a sort of plateau.

01:05:33.750 --> 01:05:36.970
And the body sort of
droops a little bit.

01:05:36.970 --> 01:05:39.750
And maybe the eyes are
sparkly, but the skin

01:05:39.750 --> 01:05:42.670
is a little blotchy and the hair
starts to gray a little bit,

01:05:42.670 --> 01:05:44.680
and it stoops a little bit more.

01:05:44.680 --> 01:05:47.160
And then some of the light
goes out of the eyes.

01:05:47.160 --> 01:05:53.840
And then there's this-- and then
13, 14 minutes into the film,

01:05:53.840 --> 01:05:57.480
there's just this
body on the floor.

01:05:57.480 --> 01:05:58.660
And the film goes on.

01:05:58.660 --> 01:06:04.110
And so the skin
dries up, disappears.

01:06:04.110 --> 01:06:05.060
It's gone.

01:06:05.060 --> 01:06:06.880
There's just a skeleton.

01:06:06.880 --> 01:06:09.700
And then gradually it starts
to crumble, turn to dust,

01:06:09.700 --> 01:06:11.900
and blows away, and it's gone.

01:06:15.240 --> 01:06:24.160
So where are you in all of this?

01:06:24.160 --> 01:06:27.000
So it begins-- I know
it's a little esoteric.

01:06:27.000 --> 01:06:28.780
But if you can
just picture that.

01:06:28.780 --> 01:06:31.554
At any moment in time,
you're obviously here.

01:06:31.554 --> 01:06:32.720
You're holding a microphone.

01:06:32.720 --> 01:06:34.170
And you know, I'm here.

01:06:34.170 --> 01:06:36.550
We're talking, et
cetera, et cetera.

01:06:36.550 --> 01:06:39.103
But on this larger
spans of time.

01:06:43.980 --> 01:06:45.860
So Buddhism is
famous for what they

01:06:45.860 --> 01:06:51.980
say is that there is
nothing essential in us

01:06:51.980 --> 01:06:54.540
that separates us
from everything else.

01:06:54.540 --> 01:06:57.130
We are just a process.

01:06:57.130 --> 01:06:59.960
And what happens-- and
this is evolutionary too--

01:06:59.960 --> 01:07:07.680
is we latch onto and identify
with what I feel right now.

01:07:07.680 --> 01:07:11.290
And if our happiness, if
the source of well-being

01:07:11.290 --> 01:07:17.640
is keeping you just like
you are right now forever,

01:07:17.640 --> 01:07:19.540
you're cooked.

01:07:19.540 --> 01:07:20.290
It won't happen.

01:07:29.190 --> 01:07:35.540
I remember the first time that
a close friend of mine died.

01:07:35.540 --> 01:07:40.825
I was a sophomore or
junior year in high school.

01:07:40.825 --> 01:07:44.610
And Larry was killed
in a car accident.

01:07:44.610 --> 01:07:49.300
And that was pretty weird, just
to actually be with all that.

01:07:49.300 --> 01:07:54.500
The strangest thing about it
all was that the next week we

01:07:54.500 --> 01:07:57.951
had our French midterm
exam right on schedule.

01:07:57.951 --> 01:08:00.362
And I remember sitting in
that French midterm taking

01:08:00.362 --> 01:08:02.320
this, because Larry used
to sit up [INAUDIBLE].

01:08:02.320 --> 01:08:03.730
I say, does anybody notice?

01:08:03.730 --> 01:08:04.670
Larry is gone.

01:08:04.670 --> 01:08:05.420
What are we doing?

01:08:05.420 --> 01:08:07.190
You know, it's like. [GROWL].

01:08:07.190 --> 01:08:10.290
I wanted to write on the
exam, [SPEAKING FRENCH].

01:08:10.290 --> 01:08:13.070
It's like, does anybody
notice the guy is gone?

01:08:13.070 --> 01:08:14.840
And I got it.

01:08:14.840 --> 01:08:18.109
You know, that when
I die, there will

01:08:18.109 --> 01:08:22.290
be a handful of people that
will mourn me for a few years.

01:08:22.290 --> 01:08:24.040
But even they will get
up the next morning

01:08:24.040 --> 01:08:27.359
and complain about politics
and everything else,

01:08:27.359 --> 01:08:30.319
that life will go on without me.

01:08:30.319 --> 01:08:34.290
And so a lot of the base tension
that we have is trying to hold

01:08:34.290 --> 01:08:39.229
on to a kind of an eternal
existence that just isn't-- it

01:08:39.229 --> 01:08:41.470
just isn't there.

01:08:41.470 --> 01:08:46.250
And so if you can imagine
sort of really getting

01:08:46.250 --> 01:08:50.630
that, that in not too many
years I'm going to be gone.

01:08:50.630 --> 01:08:53.180
And hundred years
from now I don't

01:08:53.180 --> 01:08:57.160
know if there will be any
sign I was ever on the planet.

01:08:57.160 --> 01:09:00.490
And you can feel how hard
it is to hold that thought.

01:09:00.490 --> 01:09:04.560
But if you can be with
that a little bit,

01:09:04.560 --> 01:09:06.770
it's like something relaxes.

01:09:06.770 --> 01:09:07.720
It's like, OK.

01:09:07.720 --> 01:09:12.210
You know, we're just part
of an ongoing process.

01:09:12.210 --> 01:09:15.050
And it's really OK.

01:09:15.050 --> 01:09:18.090
And as you can tap
into that a little bit,

01:09:18.090 --> 01:09:21.359
there really is a deep
kind of well-being

01:09:21.359 --> 01:09:22.979
that is behind all of it.

01:09:22.979 --> 01:09:23.740
It's not mine.

01:09:23.740 --> 01:09:25.740
It's not yours.

01:09:25.740 --> 01:09:27.670
But we're just there with it.

01:09:27.670 --> 01:09:33.950
But we want to hold
onto our job, our body,

01:09:33.950 --> 01:09:37.740
anything like that.

01:09:37.740 --> 01:09:39.240
It's a disaster.

01:09:44.870 --> 01:09:49.020
I remember-- oh, God.

01:09:49.020 --> 01:09:51.960
First time I learned
where babies came from,

01:09:51.960 --> 01:09:54.260
I was probably about--
I don't know-- five when

01:09:54.260 --> 01:09:57.087
my mother told me the story.

01:09:57.087 --> 01:09:59.170
You know, the sperm, and
the egg, and the sex act.

01:09:59.170 --> 01:09:59.836
The whole thing.

01:09:59.836 --> 01:10:03.275
And I think I had a pretty
typical five-year-old response

01:10:03.275 --> 01:10:03.775
to it.

01:10:03.775 --> 01:10:05.180
It was like, oh, you're kidding.

01:10:05.180 --> 01:10:08.100
That's gross.

01:10:08.100 --> 01:10:11.620
But I remember that night, lying
in bed looking at the ceiling

01:10:11.620 --> 01:10:16.550
and thinking, so what if my
mother and father had not

01:10:16.550 --> 01:10:20.770
gone to the University of
Michigan at the same time?

01:10:20.770 --> 01:10:24.640
What if they had not
ever fallen in love?

01:10:24.640 --> 01:10:26.280
What if they hadn't
been in the mood

01:10:26.280 --> 01:10:30.020
to start a baby at a
particular afternoon in 1947,

01:10:30.020 --> 01:10:32.260
or whenever it was?

01:10:32.260 --> 01:10:35.470
What if a different one
of those five million

01:10:35.470 --> 01:10:37.350
sperm, whatever it
is, hit the egg?

01:10:37.350 --> 01:10:40.140
I could just think of
a zillion contingencies

01:10:40.140 --> 01:10:43.900
in which I would not exist.

01:10:43.900 --> 01:10:46.180
And nobody would notice.

01:10:46.180 --> 01:10:48.332
The wouldn't even miss me.

01:10:48.332 --> 01:10:50.040
They'd probably have
another second child

01:10:50.040 --> 01:10:52.890
and give him my name.

01:10:52.890 --> 01:10:56.215
You know, that our existence
here is such a fluke.

01:10:59.380 --> 01:11:05.229
And if we really get that,
it's actually-- at first

01:11:05.229 --> 01:11:06.020
it's kind of scary.

01:11:06.020 --> 01:11:09.350
But we really get it, it's
actually quite joyful,

01:11:09.350 --> 01:11:10.490
you know?

01:11:10.490 --> 01:11:13.080
Cause every moment's a gift.

01:11:18.817 --> 01:11:19.900
And that can be wonderful.

01:11:19.900 --> 01:11:25.760
And the next moment, I go
back to the prehistoric scene.

01:11:25.760 --> 01:11:27.110
walking through the jungle.

01:11:27.110 --> 01:11:30.876
There is one guy who is
at one with everything.

01:11:30.876 --> 01:11:31.830
The trees.

01:11:31.830 --> 01:11:34.180
The lakes.

01:11:34.180 --> 01:11:36.250
The saber tooth kitties.

01:11:36.250 --> 01:11:37.510
The big bears.

01:11:37.510 --> 01:11:39.620
It's all lovely.

01:11:39.620 --> 01:11:42.965
And there's another guy who
is frightened of everything.

01:11:42.965 --> 01:11:44.530
A little rustle,
and he runs around

01:11:44.530 --> 01:11:47.970
like a paranoid squirrel.

01:11:47.970 --> 01:11:52.160
Guess whose DNA we got?

01:11:52.160 --> 01:11:53.910
I look at the squirrels
running out there.

01:11:53.910 --> 01:11:55.170
You know, it's like whoa!

01:11:55.170 --> 01:11:57.691
They are like so uptight.

01:11:57.691 --> 01:11:59.190
But if they relax
a little bit, they

01:11:59.190 --> 01:12:02.030
get eaten by the next
dog that came along.

01:12:02.030 --> 01:12:03.930
So that's been bred into us.

01:12:03.930 --> 01:12:06.230
But it's not metaphysical.

01:12:06.230 --> 01:12:08.970
You know, it's not
how reality is.

01:12:08.970 --> 01:12:14.264
It's just an artifact of
evolutionary processes.

01:12:18.255 --> 01:12:18.755
Wow.

01:12:18.755 --> 01:12:20.751
I didn't expect to [INAUDIBLE].

01:12:24.807 --> 01:12:25.390
Anything more?

01:12:25.390 --> 01:12:26.348
Or have you had enough?

01:12:31.750 --> 01:12:39.696
So let me close with my
favorite poem of all time.

01:12:39.696 --> 01:12:42.634
It kind of touches
on some of the things

01:12:42.634 --> 01:12:52.790
you've been talking about, which
is peacefulness, equanimity,

01:12:52.790 --> 01:12:55.890
and where you find it.

01:12:55.890 --> 01:12:57.498
This poem about equanimity.

01:13:00.080 --> 01:13:03.220
It was written by
Donald C. Babcock.

01:13:03.220 --> 01:13:06.780
"Now we're ready to look at
something pretty special.

01:13:06.780 --> 01:13:12.300
It is a duck, riding the ocean
100 feet beyond the surf.

01:13:12.300 --> 01:13:13.490
No, it isn't a gull.

01:13:13.490 --> 01:13:17.260
A gull always has a
raucous touch about him.

01:13:17.260 --> 01:13:19.420
This is some sort of duck.

01:13:19.420 --> 01:13:22.670
And he cuddles in the swell.

01:13:22.670 --> 01:13:23.670
He isn't cold.

01:13:23.670 --> 01:13:27.410
And he is thinking things over.

01:13:27.410 --> 01:13:29.895
There's a big heaving
in the Atlantic.

01:13:29.895 --> 01:13:33.310
And he is a part of it.

01:13:33.310 --> 01:13:37.060
He looks a bit like a Mandarin
with a Lord Buddha meditating

01:13:37.060 --> 01:13:38.855
under the Bodhi tree.

01:13:38.855 --> 01:13:41.355
But he has hardly enough about
the eyes to be a philosopher.

01:13:44.050 --> 01:13:50.120
He has poise, however, which
is what philosophers must have.

01:13:50.120 --> 01:13:53.530
He can rest while the
Atlantic heaves because he

01:13:53.530 --> 01:13:55.786
rests in the Atlantic.

01:13:58.780 --> 01:14:02.560
Probably he doesn't know
how large the ocean is.

01:14:02.560 --> 01:14:05.090
And neither do you.

01:14:05.090 --> 01:14:07.850
But he realizes it.

01:14:07.850 --> 01:14:12.070
And what does he do, I ask you.

01:14:12.070 --> 01:14:14.880
He sits down in it.

01:14:14.880 --> 01:14:19.080
He reposes in the immediate
as if it were infinity,

01:14:19.080 --> 01:14:21.070
which it is.

01:14:21.070 --> 01:14:22.430
That is religion.

01:14:22.430 --> 01:14:24.770
And the duck has it.

01:14:24.770 --> 01:14:27.120
He has made himself
part of the boundless

01:14:27.120 --> 01:14:32.270
by easing himself into it
just where it touches him.

01:14:32.270 --> 01:14:34.320
I like the little duck.

01:14:34.320 --> 01:14:35.812
He doesn't know much.

01:14:35.812 --> 01:14:43.140
But he has religion."

01:14:43.140 --> 01:14:44.850
So thank you all for coming.

01:14:44.850 --> 01:14:48.460
And thank you for your questions
and your good attention.

01:14:48.460 --> 01:14:55.170
And may we all learn how
to sit down in the waves.

01:14:58.230 --> 01:15:02.380
As far back as we can see into
history there have been waves.

01:15:02.380 --> 01:15:04.060
They will always be there.

01:15:04.060 --> 01:15:08.380
The art is learning how to sit
down in them, to rest in them.

01:15:08.380 --> 01:15:13.980
That's where the true
peace comes from.

01:15:13.980 --> 01:15:14.520
Namaste.

01:15:14.520 --> 01:15:18.190
